docs/guides/03-coercing-data.md
     1→# Coercing Data
     3→Sometimes while validating input data you'll actually want to "coerce" it to change it in someway to help validation pass. The most common example of this is adding default values to properties, but it can also be used to parse multiple input formats, or cleanup inconsistent data.
     4→
     5→To allow for these use cases, Superstruct has a concept called "coercion", which allows you to encode specific logic about how to transform a piece of data before validating it.
     6→
     7→## Default Values
    49→## Custom Coercions

docs/guides/04-refining-validation.md
     1→# Refining Validation
     3→There are some cases where you want to create a validation that is more fine-grained than a "type". For example, you might want not just a `string`, but a specific format of string. Or not just a `User`, but a user that is also an administrator.
     4→
     5→For these situations, you can use "refinements". Refinements allow you to create a new struct that is derived from an existing struct with an extra bit of validation layered on top.
     6→
     7→## Built-in Refinements
    47→## Custom Refinements

docs/guides/05-handling-errors.md
     1→# Handling Errors
     3→By default Superstruct throws errors that are easy to understand for developers. This means that out of the box you'll get nice errors messages that help you track down why a piece of data is invalid.
     4→
     5→For example, consider a simple `User` struct:
     6→
     7→```ts
     8→const User = object({
     9→  id: number(),
    10→  name: string(),
    11→  email: email(),
    12→})
    13→```
    14→
    15→If you pass in an invalid email, an error will be thrown:
    16→
    17→```ts
    18→const data = {
    19→  id: 1,
    20→  name: 'Alex',
    21→  email: false,
    22→}
    23→
    24→assert(data, User)
    25→// StructError: At path: email -- Expected a string, but received: false
    26→```
    27→
    28→You can also specify your own message for more clarity. In this case the original message will be preserved in [Error.cause](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Error/cause).
    29→
    30→```ts
    31→assert(data, User, "The user is invalid!");
    32→// StructError: The user is invalid!
    33→```
    34→
    35→In addition to the error message, the `error` object will have a bunch of useful properties on it:
    36→
    37→```ts
    38→StructError {
    39→  value: false,
    40→  key: 'email',
    41→  type: 'string',
    42→  refinement: undefined,
    43→  path: ['email'],
    44→  branch: [{ id: 1, name: 'Alex', email: false }, false],
    45→  failures: [Function]
    46→}
    47→```
    48→
      →…
