docs/guides/06-using-typescript.md
     1→# Using TypeScript
     3→Superstruct is built with TypeScript, and is designed to integrate seamlessly with its guards and assertions. Which means that if you're using TypeScript too you'll get compile-time typings for your data.
     4→
     5→> 🤖 Warning: You must enable TypeScript's [`strictNullChecks`](https://www.typescriptlang.org/tsconfig#strictNullChecks) option in your `tsconfig.json` for Superstruct to work properly with "optional" types. Note that `strictNullChecks` is disabled by default. If you enable `strict`, `strictNullChecks` will automatically be enabled.
     6→
     7→## Narrowing Types
    37→## Describing Types
    55→## Inferring Types

docs/readme.md
     7→### Usage
     9→Superstruct allows you to define the shape of data you want to validate:
    10→
    11→```js
    12→import { assert, object, number, string, array } from 'superstruct'
    13→
    14→const Article = object({
    15→  id: number(),
    16→  title: string(),
    17→  tags: array(string()),
    18→  author: object({
    19→    id: number(),
    20→  }),
    21→})
    22→
    23→const data = {
    24→  id: 34,
    25→  title: 'Hello World',
    26→  tags: ['news', 'features'],
    27→  author: {
    28→    id: 1,
    29→  },
    30→}
    31→
    32→assert(data, Article)
    33→// This will throw an error when the data is invalid.
    34→// If you'd rather not throw, you can use `is()` or `validate()`.
    35→```
    36→
    37→Superstruct ships with validators for all the common JavaScript data types, and you can define custom ones too:
    38→
    39→```js
      →…

